The Atkinson Hyperlegible font is specifically designed to enhance legibility by making individual letters more distinguishable, particularly for readers with visual impairments. It is a popular webfont that can be integrated into websites to improve accessibility. You can use it by including it in your project via its [official repository](https://github.com/brailleapps/Atkinson-Hyperlegible) or by linking to it in your CSS, for example:

css
@font-face {
  font-family: 'Atkinson Hyperlegible';
  src: url('path/to/atkinson-hyperlegible.woff2') format('woff2');
}

To ensure WCAG compliance for typography, developers should:
1. Use fonts that meet WCAG's contrast and legibility criteria, such as Atkinson Hyperlegible.
2. Provide sufficient contrast between text and background (e.g., at least 4.5:1 for normal text).
3. Avoid decorative or overly stylized fonts that hinder readability.
4. Test typography in various contexts, including mobile devices and screen readers.
5. Stay updated with WCAG 3 and its APCA algorithm, which introduces more advanced contrast metrics. For example, you can use CSS to enforce legibility:

css
body {
  font-family: 'Atkinson Hyperlegible', sans-serif;
  color: #000000;
  background-color: #ffffff;
  line-height: 1.5;
}
